com.analog.lyric.dimple.model.transform

Class VariableEliminator

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.analog.lyric.dimple.model.transform.VariableEliminator

  • public class VariableEliminator
extends java.lang.Object
    Computes a variable elimination order for a factor graph using a greedy algorithm over various cost functions.

    A variable elimination order is an ordering of the variables in a graph that is intended to minimize the cost of various exact inference algorithms that are based on it. While the exact inference cost will depend on the algorithm, in general, orderings that minimize the cost of the classic variable elimination algorithm are also good for other algorithms as well, including the construction of junction trees, finding loop cuts for loop cut conditioning, and for constructing graph partition trees for recursive conditioning schemes.

    The problem of finding an optimal ordering is NP-hard, but the heuristic greed approach implemented by this class has been shown to produce good results with reasonable time complexity. The algorithm implemented here is as follows:

    1. Build a variable to variable adjacency list representation for the variables in the factor graph. Note that this representation will be modified during the execution of the algorithm so the actual model representation cannot be used directly.
    2. Pick a cost function that will be used to order variables in the graph. The specific cost functions will be described below.
    3. Build a priority queue (heap) containing all of the variables ordered according to cost, with the minimum cost at the front.
    4. While the priority queue is not empty:
      1. Remove the variable with the lowest cost from the queue.
      2. Add the variable to the end of the variable elimination order
      3. Connect all of the variable's neighbors with each other by adding edges as necessary.
      4. Remove the variable from the graph by removing it from its neighbors adjacency sets.
      5. Update the priority queue as appropriate to reflect the changes to the value of the cost function resulting from the changes to the graph.

    There are four standard cost functions that are described in the literature and supported by this implementation:

    • VariableEliminator.VariableCost.MIN_NEIGHBORS
    • VariableEliminator.VariableCost.WEIGHTED_MIN_NEIGHBORS
    • VariableEliminator.VariableCost.MIN_FILL
    • VariableEliminator.VariableCost.WEIGHTED_MIN_FILL
    Users can implement additional cost functions by subclassing VariableEliminator.CostFunction.

    NOTE: this implementation currently does not handle models that contain non-Discrete variables unless they have fixed values and usesConditioning() is true. It also and it does not take into account the contents of the factor tables.

    • Method Detail

      • generate

        public static VariableEliminator.Ordering generate(FactorGraph model,
                                   boolean useConditioning,
                                   int nAttempts,
                                   VariableEliminator.Stats threshold,
                                   VariableEliminator.VariableCost... costFunctions)
        Computes a variable elimination order by iteratively retrying using one or more cost functions and choosing the best fit according to the specified threshold statistics.

        This function builds an eliminator for specified mode and useConditioning attribute. It then iteratively up to nAttempts times picks a cost function at random from costFunctions and uses it to build an VariableEliminator.OrderIterator from which it generates an ordering. After each iteration, the global statistics (from the getStats() method on the iterator) are compared against the best statistics so far using the statistic's compareTo method to determine whether to keep the ordering. If the stats at any point satisfy the specified threshold values (as determined by the meetsThreshold method then the function will return immediately.

        For example, the following call will generate an order by conditioning out any fixed value variables, and will randomly try weighted min neighbors or weighted min fill cost functions up to ten iterations and returning the first one to achieve a max clique cardinality of no more than 42, otherwise returns the order with the best max clique cardinality: 

        Ordering order = generateStochastically(fg, true, 10,
         new Stats().maxCliqueCardinality(42),
         VariableCost.WEIGHTED_MIN_NEIGHBORS, VariableCost.WEIGHTED_MIN_FILL)

        Parameters:
        model - is the graph for which the eliminator order is being computed.
        useConditioning - specifies whether to use conditioning (see usesConditioning()
        nAttempts - is the number of potential iteration orders to compute. If not a positive value, then each cost function will be tried once deterministically.
        threshold - specifies which statistics should be used to evaluate the goodness of a given ordering (see VariableEliminator.Stats.compareTo(com.analog.lyric.dimple.model.transform.VariableEliminator.Stats, com.analog.lyric.dimple.model.transform.VariableEliminator.Stats)) and also threshold values for each statistic that will terminate the function before all nAttempts have been tried (see VariableEliminator.Stats.meetsThreshold(com.analog.lyric.dimple.model.transform.VariableEliminator.Stats)). Only statistics with non-negative threshold values will be considered.
        costFunctions - is a list of cost functions to be used. If empty, all will be tried.
        Returns:
        the variable elimination order that best satisfied the threshold statistics.

      • usesConditioning

        public boolean usesConditioning()
        True if eliminator takes into account variables that are conditioned with a fixed value. If true, then such variables will be eliminated first and will be treated as if they have no siblings. Value is set during construction.
